 the rise across Europe, The wolves are coming back offers an insight into the rise of the far right in Germany. The nationalist Alternative for Germany represents the third-largest party in the German federal parliament, with representation in the vast majority of German states. They draw much of their support from the ‘post-traumatic places’ in Eastern Germany, regions structured by realities of disownment, disenfranchisement and a lack of democratic infrastructure. Pates and Leser provide an account of the societal roots of a new group of radical right parties, whose existence and success we always assumed to be impossible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aEast Germany.  aaffects in politics.  ademocracy in action.  afar right politics.  amigration.  anationalism.  apolitical ethnography.  apolitics of fear.  apopulism.  aprotest.1 aLeser, Julia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLeser, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPates, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615023340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526150233423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526150233/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles